1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,491
John got the smallest office and fizzled out.

2
00:00:04,160 --> 00:00:14,051
Several years ago, I observed small thinking about an office assignment destroy a young fellow's chances for a profitable career in advertising.

3
00:00:14,480 --> 00:00:20,210
Four young executives, all on the same status level, were moved into new offices.

4
00:00:20,480 --> 00:00:24,531
Three of the offices were identical in size and decoration.

5
00:00:24,800 --> 00:00:27,891
The fourth was smaller and less elaborate.

6
00:00:28,401 --> 00:00:31,491
J.M. was assigned the fourth office.

7
00:00:31,680 --> 00:00:34,531
This turned out to be a real blow to his pride.

8
00:00:34,640 --> 00:00:37,491
Immediately, he felt discriminated against.

9
00:00:37,921 --> 00:00:42,210
Negative thinking, resentment, bitterness, jealousy built up.

10
00:00:42,401 --> 00:00:44,931
J.M. began to feel inadequate.

11
00:00:45,200 --> 00:00:49,730
The result was that J.M. grew hostile toward his fellow executives.

12
00:00:49,921 --> 00:00:54,531
Rather than cooperate, he did his best to undermine their efforts.

13
00:00:54,800 --> 00:00:56,051
Things got worse.

14
00:00:56,080 --> 00:01:02,931
Three months later, J.M. slipped so badly that management had no choice but to issue him a pink slip.

15
00:01:03,600 --> 00:01:10,931
Small thinking over a very small matter stopped J.M. In his haste to feel he was discriminated against,

16
00:01:11,120 --> 00:01:17,810
J.M. failed to observe that the company was expanding rapidly and office space was at a premium.

17
00:01:18,080 --> 00:01:26,691
He didn't stop to consider the possibility that the executive who made the office assignments didn't even know which one was the smallest.

18
00:01:26,960 --> 00:01:33,571
No one in the organization, except JM, regarded his office as an index of his value.

19
00:01:34,160 --> 00:01:40,131
Small thinking about unimportant things, like seeing your name last on the department root sheet,

20
00:01:40,160 --> 00:01:43,810
or getting the fourth carbon of an office memo, can hurt you.

21
00:01:44,080 --> 00:01:48,290
Think big, and none of these little things can hold you back.

22
00:01:48,290 --> 00:01:50,051
4.

23
00:01:50,480 --> 00:01:53,011
Even stuttering is a detail.

24
00:01:53,520 --> 00:01:59,330
A sales executive told me how even stuttering is a mere detail in salesmanship,

25
00:01:59,361 --> 00:02:02,451
if the fellow has the really important qualities.

26
00:02:03,040 --> 00:02:08,370
I have a friend, also a sales executive, who loves to play practical jokes,

27
00:02:08,480 --> 00:02:11,571
though sometimes these jokes aren't jokes at all.

28
00:02:11,841 --> 00:02:18,210
A few months ago, a young fellow called on my practical joking friend and asked for a sales job.

29
00:02:18,401 --> 00:02:25,171
The fellow had a terrible stutter, though, and my friend decided right here was a chance to play a joke on me.

30
00:02:25,441 --> 00:02:31,091
So the friend told the stammering applicant that he wasn't in the market for a salesman right now,

31
00:02:31,120 --> 00:02:34,370
but one of his friends, me, had a spot to fill.

32
00:02:34,480 --> 00:02:38,451
Then he phoned me, and boy did he give this fellow a build-up.

33
00:02:38,560 --> 00:02:42,370
Not suspecting anything, I said, send him right over.

34
00:02:42,960 --> 00:02:45,411
Thirty minutes later, in he walked.

35
00:02:45,520 --> 00:02:51,651
The young fellow hadn't said three words before I knew why my friend was so eager to send him over.

36
00:02:52,000 --> 00:02:55,891
I-I-I'm J-J-Jack R., he said.

37
00:02:56,160 --> 00:03:01,491
Mr. X sent me over t-t-to talk t-t-to you about a j-j-job.

38
00:03:01,841 --> 00:03:04,210
Almost every word was a struggle.

39
00:03:04,480 --> 00:03:10,210
I thought to myself, this guy couldn't sell a dollar bill for ninety cents on Wall Street.

40
00:03:10,480 --> 00:03:14,611
I was sore at my friend, but I really felt sorry for this fellow,

41
00:03:14,640 --> 00:03:22,691
so I thought the least I could do was to ask him some polite questions while I thought up a good excuse as to why I couldn't use him.

42
00:03:23,361 --> 00:03:28,051
As we talked on, however, I discovered this fellow was no stoop.

43
00:03:28,080 --> 00:03:29,411
He was intelligent.

44
00:03:29,520 --> 00:03:31,730
He handled himself very nicely.

45
00:03:31,841 --> 00:03:35,330
But I just couldn't overlook the fact that he stuttered.

46
00:03:35,600 --> 00:03:40,850
Finally, I decided I'd wind up the interview by asking one last question.

47
00:03:41,200 --> 00:03:43,730
What makes you think you can sell?

48
00:03:44,560 --> 00:03:52,131
Well, he said, I learn fast, I like people, I think you've got a good company,

49
00:03:52,240 --> 00:03:55,651
and I want to make money.

50
00:03:55,921 --> 00:04:05,651
Now, I do have a speech impairment, but that doesn't bother me, so why should it bother anybody else?

51
00:04:06,401 --> 00:04:11,971
His answer showed me he had all the really important qualifications for a salesman.

52
00:04:12,240 --> 00:04:14,770
I decided right then to give him a chance.

53
00:04:14,800 --> 00:04:17,651
And you know, he's working out very well.

54
00:04:18,401 --> 00:04:25,971
Even a speech impairment in a talker's profession is a triviality if the person has the big qualities.

